{{FieldValueSerializerHelper.CastingSerializer}} is trying to convert value using boxing conversion. It will always fail if destination type does not match source type (the only exclusion is the situation when source type inherits from destination type).

{code:java}
_serializer.Serialize(context, args, (TTo)(object)value);
{code}

Boxing conversion omits user-defined type conversion therefor custom {{TypeConverter}} nor {{implicit operator}} conversions won't work.

Please add support for user-defined implicit type casting to the predicate translator.

I've prepared pull request that implements the requested feature. It might help with CSHARP-1890, CSHARP-1891 if I'm not mistaken. This approach will also allow implicit casting of primitive types out of the box, for example:

{code:java}
//Int32 (1) will be automatically casted to string value ("1")
SomeCollection<Example>().AsQueryable().Where(x=>x.StringValue == (object)1);
//{"StringValue": "1"}
{code}

Quick note. This problem arose in an upgrade from 2.2 to 2.4.2.

When doing the following:
{code:title=SomeMethod}
  var filt1 = Builders<Thing>.Filter.Empty;
  var filt2 = Builders<Thing>.Filter.Empty;
  var filter = Builders<Thing>.Filter.And(filt1,filt2);
{code}

The rendered "filter" from above is an empty (and illegal) $and: {[]}

in version 2.2, this would render as empty.

When a non-nullable enum field is compared to a nullable value the filter does not render correctly.

To reproduce use these types:

{code}
public enum E { A, B }

public class C
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    [BsonRepresentation(BsonType.String)]
    public E E { get; set; }
}
{code}

And this code:

{code}
var builder = Builders<C>.Filter;
var value = (E?)E.A;
var filter = builder.Where(x => x.E == value);
var registry = BsonSerializer.SerializerRegistry;
var serializer = registry.GetSerializer<C>();
var rendered = filter.Render(serializer, registry).ToJson();
{code}

The filter renders as:

{code}
"{ \"E\" : 0 }"
{code}

but should have rendered as:

{code}
"{ \"E\" : \"A\" }"
{code}

because the underlying field serializer uses String representation.

Given the class and enum:

{code}
class Person
{
	public Color FavoriteColor { get; set; }
}

enum Color
{
	Blue,
	SomethingElse
}
{code}

The following code snippet will not work:

{code}
Builders<Person>.IndexKeys.Ascending(x => x.FavoriteColor);
Builders<Person>.Filter.Eq(x => x.FavoriteColor, Color.Blue);
// other builders as well
{code}

h4. Workaround

Use the string field name of the member. Even if you have mapped it to a different element name, as long as the member name is used, it will still get mapped:

{code}
Builders<Person>.IndexKeys.Ascending("FavoriteColor");
{code}

